[[File:Yahgan basket.jpg|thumb|220px|Traditional [[Yahgan]] basket, woven by Abuela Cristina Calderón, Chile, photo by Jim Cadwell]] '''Cristina Calderón''' (born May 24, 1928 at Robalo, [[Puerto Williams]] on [[Navarino Island]], [[Chile]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contenidoslocales.cl/comunidad/7644/cristina-calderon-representara-la-region-de-magallanes-en-la-eleccion-de-la-mujer-del |title=Cristina Calderón representará a la Región de Magallanes en la elección de la mujer del Bicentenario |author=Cristian Muñoz Vera |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=24 May 2011 |language=spanish }}</ref> is the last living full-blooded [[Yaghan people|Yaghan]] person after the death of her sister Úrsula in 2003.<ref name="EA2011">{{cite web |url= http://www.estrellaarica.cl/site/edic/20030817234728/pags/20030818041915.html |title= Mujer yagana busca preservar lengua a través de diccionario |accessdate=19 March 2011 |last= Azúa |first= Mauricio |date= |publisher= La Estrella de Arica |language=spanish }}</ref> By 2004, Calderón (often referred to as simply ''Abuela'', Spanish for Grandmother) and her sister-in-law Emelinda Acuña were the only two remaining native speakers of the [[Yaghan language]].<ref name=NYT2004>{{cite news|title=Say No More|author=Jack Hitt|authorlink=Jack Hitt|newspaper=The New York Times Magazine|publisher=The New York Times|location=New York|issn=0028-7822|date=February 29, 2004|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/29/magazine/say-no-more.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|accessdate=October 4, 2011|page=52}}</ref> After Acuña died at 84 years of age (October 12, 2005), Calderón became the last living full-blooded Yaghan person.<ref name=ST2005>{{cite news|title=Extinction on the horizon for indigenous tribe in Chile: Second-To-Last Yagana Woman Dies Of A Heart Attack|author=Jackie Hailey|newspaper=The Santiago Times|location=Santiago|date=October 14, 2005|url=http://www.mapuche-nation.org/english/html/news/n-88.htm|accessdate=October 4, 2011}}</ref> With her granddaughter Cristina Zarraga and her sister Úrsula Calderon she published a book of Yaghan stories called ''Hai Kur Mamashu Shis'' (''I Want to Tell You a Story'') in 2005.
As of May 2017, she was still alive and well in her hometown, [[Puerto Williams]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/mundo/2017/05/12/la-abuela-cristina-la-ultima-habitante-de-la-etnia-del-fin-del-mundo/ |title=La abuela Cristina la ultima habitante de la etnia del fin del mundo |accessdate=January 16, 2018}}</ref>
Cristina Calderón has been officially declared ''Illustrious Daughter of [[Magallanes Region|the Magallanes Region and Chilean Antarctica]]''. She also has been recognized by the [[National Council of Culture and the Arts (Chile)]] as a ''Living Human Treasure'' in the framework of the Convention for the Safeguard of Immaterial Heritage, adopted by [[UNESCO]] in 2003. Likewise, she was nominated to be one of the fifty heroines in the celebration of the [[Bicentennial of Chile]].<ref name="BC2011">{{cite web |author=[[Radio Bío-Bío|Biobíochile.cl]] |title=Última representante del pueblo Yagan cumple 83 años en Puerto Williams |url=http://www.biobiochile.cl/2011/05/26/ultima-representante-del-pueblo-yagan-cumple-83-anos-en-puerto-williams.shtml |date=May 26, 2011 |accessdate=28 May 2011 |language=spanish }}</ref>
