{{Infobox language |name=Galoli |nativename=Galolen |states=[[East Timor]] |region=[[Manatuto District]] |speakers={{sigfig|10530|2}}<ref>Excluding 3,150 Dadu'a speakers per the census</ref> |date=2010 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] (MP) |fam3=[[Nuclear Malayo-Polynesian languages|Nuclear MP]] |fam4=([[Central–Eastern Malayo-Polynesian languages|Central–Eastern]]) |fam5=[[Timor–Babar languages|Timor–Babar]] |fam6=Wetar–Galoli |dia1=Talur |iso3=gal |glotto=galo1243 |glottorefname=Galoli |map=Galoli.png |mapcaption=Distribution of Galoli mother tongue-speakers in East Timor. Galoli is also spoken on the south coast of [[Wetar Island]] in Indonesia, just off the top of the map. }}
The '''Galoli''', or '''Galolen''', are a people of [[East Timor]] with a population of about 50,000, primarily along the northern coast of the district of [[Manatuto District|Manatuto]]. To the west lies the [[Mambai people (Timor)|Mambai]] people. There is an old colony on the southern coast of [[Wetar]] island, the Talo, who speak the Talur dialect.
Their language, also known as Galoli, is one of the [[Timor–Babar languages|Timor–Babar]] group of [[Austronesian languages]]. It is one of the [[national language]]s designated by the constitution of East Timor. Because the area was used as a trading center for different cultures, there are a large number of foreign loan words in the vocabulary, principally from Moluccan and [[Malay language|Malay]] languages. Although it is not spoken by as many people as other national languages, it was adopted by the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in the district of [[Manatuto District|Manatuto]] and thus has become fixed in grammars and dictionaries.
==Alphabet== '''A B D E G H I K L M N O R S T U ' '''
The ''' ' ''' mark represents a glottal stop, [ʔ].<ref>[https://www.omniglot.com/writing/galoli.htm Galoli language], Omniglot.</ref>
