{{Infobox language | name = Warao | nativename = | states = [[Venezuela]], [[Guyana]], [[Suriname]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]] | ethnicity = [[Warao people|Warao]] | speakers = 32,800 | date = 2005-2011 | ref = e19 | familycolor = American | family = [[Language isolate]] | iso3 = wba | glotto = wara1303 | glottorefname = Warao | map = Warao language.png | mapcaption = }}
'''Warao''' (also known as '''Guarauno''', '''Guarao''', '''Warrau''') is the native language of the [[Warao people]]. A [[language isolate]], it is spoken by about 33,000 people primarily in northern [[Venezuela]], [[Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Guyana]] and [[Suriname]]. It is notable for its unusual [[object–subject–verb]] [[word order]].<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.jorojokowarao.de/Doku/Warao3.html | title=Warao | publisher=www.jorojokowarao.de | accessdate=2013-09-22}}</ref> The 2015 Venezuelan film ''[[Gone with the River]]'' was spoken in Warao.<ref name="film">{{cite web|url=http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Venezuelan-Film-in-Indigenous-Warao-Language-an-Oscar-Hopeful-20150911-0052.html |title=Venezuelan Film in Indigenous Warao Language an Oscar Hopeful |work=telesurtv |date=12 September 2015 |accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>
==Population== The language had an estimated 28,100 speakers in [[Venezuela]] as of 2007. The [[Warao people]] live chiefly in the [[Orinoco Delta]] region of northeastern Venezuela, with smaller communities in southwestern [[Trinidad]] ([[Trinidad and Tobago]]), western [[Guyana]] and [[Suriname]].<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/14/show_language.asp?code=WBA "WARAO: a language of Venezuela"], ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World'', 14th Edition, 2000</ref> The language is considered endangered by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-1964.html|title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-03-20}}</ref>
==Grammar== The language's basic [[word order]] has been analyzed as [[object–subject–verb]], a very rare word order among [[nominative–accusative language]]s such as Warao.<ref>{{cite journal|url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0024384185902815 | doi=10.1016/S0024-3841(85)90281-5 | volume=66 | issue=2–3 | title=OSV as the basic order in Warao | year=1985 | journal=Lingua | pages=115–134 | last1 = Romero-Figueroa | first1 = Andrés}}</ref>
=== Phonology === Warao phonology is similar to that of [[Japanese phonology|Japanese]]. The Warao consonant inventory is relatively simple: {| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" ! rowspan="2" | ! rowspan="2" | [[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! colspan="2" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- class="small" ! plain !! [[labialized]] |- ! [[Stop consonant|Plosive]] | {{IPA|p}} | {{IPA|t}} | | {{IPA|k}} | {{IPA|kʷ}} | |- ! [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | | {{IPA|s}} | | | | {{IPA|h}} |- ! [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | {{IPA|m}} | {{IPA|n}} | | | | |- ![[Tap consonant|Flap]] | |ɾ | | | | |- ! [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | {{IPA|j}} | | {{IPA|w}} | |} /b/ and /d, l̆/ are allophones of /{{IPA|p}}/ and /ɾ/. There are five oral vowels {{IPA|/a, ɛ, i, ɔ, u/}} and five nasal vowels {{IPA|/ã, ẽ, ĩ, õ, ũ/}}. /u/ after /k/ within the beginning of words has a sound as /ɨ/.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Warao I: Phonology and Morphophonemics|last=Osborn Jr.|first=Henry A.|publisher=International Journal of American Linguistics|year=1966|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>
==Relatives== Warao appears to be a [[language isolate]], unrelated to any recorded language in the region or elsewhere.<ref>Campbell & Grondona, 2012, ''The Indigenous Languages of South America: A Comprehensive Guide''</ref> Terrence Kaufman (1994) included it in his hypothetical [[Macro-Paezan]] family, but the necessary supporting work was never done.<ref>Campbell, Lyle. (1997). ''American Indian languages: The historical linguistics of Native America. New York: Oxford University Press''. {{ISBN|0-19-509427-1}}.</ref> Julian Granberry connected many of the grammatical forms, including nominal and verbal [[suffixes]], of Warao to the [[Timucua language]] of North Florida, also a language isolate.<ref>Julian Granberry, ''A Grammar and Dictionary of the Timucua Language'', pp. 15-32</ref> However, he has also derives Timucua morphemes from Muskogean, Chibchan, Paezan, Arawakan, and other Amazonian languages, suggesting multi-language [[creolization]] as a possible explanation for these similarities. This notion has met with skepticism and described by [[Lyle Campbell]] as "in no way convincing".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/AmericanIndianLanguagesTheHistoricalLinguisticsOfNativeAmerica/American%20Indian%20Languages%20The%20Historical%20Linguistics%20of%20Native%20America_djvu.txt|title=Full text of "American Indian Languages The Historical Linguistics Of Native America"|website=archive.org|language=en|access-date=2017-06-06}}</ref>
Granberry also finds "Waroid" vocabulary items in [[Goajiro language|Guajiro]] (from toponymic evidence it seems that the Warao or a related people once occupied Goajiro country) and in [[Taino language|Taino]] (''nuçay/nozay'' [nosái] "gold" in Ciboney — cf. Warao ''naséi símo'' "gold" (lit. "yellow pebble") — and ''duho'' "ceremonial stool" in Classic Taino — cf. Warao ''duhu'' "sit, stool"). Granberry & Vescelius (2004) note that toponymic evidence suggests that the pre-Taino [[Macorix language]] of Hispaniola and [[Guanahatabey language]] of Cuba may have been Waroid languages as well.
